  "doc_id": "48622",
  "text": "Data from short and long-term studies in bipolar subjects indicates that aripiprazole has a good tolerability and safety profile. During the acute three-week monotherapy trials, the most commonly noted adverse effects versus placebo were akathisia (13% vs. 4%), sedation (8% vs. 3%), restlessness (6% vs. 3%), tremor (6% vs. 3%), and EPSE (5% vs. 2%) [CITATION_1] [20] . In a six-week study of aripiprazole adjunctive to mood stabilizers, akathisia (19% v. 5%), insomnia (8% v. 4%), and extrapyramidal side effects (5% vs. 1%) were most frequently described [CITATION_2] . Two recurrence prevention trials for 52 and 100 weeks showed tremor, akathisia, hypertension, and dry mouth to be the common side effects [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Across the long-term trials, the most common treatment-emergent adverse events that lead to treatment discontinuation in aripiprazole recipients were mania (1%) or manic reaction (7%), akathisia (5%), and tremor (2%).",
